Python 3.12 on Android:
platform.system(): kernel name, e.g. "Linux"
platform.release(): kernel version, e.g. "4.14.190-lineage-gef0cb31b13"
os.uname().sysname: kernel name, e.g. "Linux"
os.uname().release: kernel version, e.g. "4.14.190-lineage-gef0cb31b13"

Python 3.13 on Android:
platform.system(): OS name, e.g. "Android"
platform.release(): OS version, e.g. "13"
os.uname().sysname: kernel name, e.g. "Linux"
os.uname().release: kernel version, e.g. "4.14.190-lineage-gef0cb31b13"

udocker was written for, and expects, the previous behavior when running in Python on Android,
so use os.uname() instead of platform, which is the same as the previous behavior, and unlikely to change.

--- a/udocker/helper/hostinfo.py
+++ b/udocker/helper/hostinfo.py
@@ -30,16 +30,16 @@ class HostInfo(ArchInfo):
         return arch[0] if arch[0] else ""
 
     def osversion(self):
-        """Get operating system"""
+        """Get operating system kernel name"""
         try:
-            return platform.system().lower()
+            return os.uname().sysname.lower()
         except (NameError, AttributeError):
             return ""
 
     def oskernel(self):
-        """Get operating system"""
+        """Get operating system kernel version"""
         try:
-            return platform.release()
+            return os.uname().release
         except (NameError, AttributeError):
             return "6.1.1"
 
